titleproper.value:
Guide to the Jay Gorney Papers
                    <num>TAM.152</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Sally Jhehan Roberts

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-29T18:39-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: Jay Gorney (1896-1990) was a composer for musical theater, most notably of the Depression-era hit, “Brother, Can You Spare a Dime?” He was questioned by the House Committee on Un-American Activities (HUAC) on May 6, 1953 regarding his participation in pro-Communist groups and publications. This collection contains biographical material, documents concerning Gorney’s appearance before HUAC, files on him compiled by the FBI, and sheet music of songs with a political slant.

p.value:
Published citations should take the following form:

                <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives 
                <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 
                <lb/>70 Washington Square South 
                <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

Sources: Gorney, Sondra K. 
                <emph render="italic">Brother, Can You Spare a Dime?: The Life of Composer Jay Gorney</emph>. Lanham, MD.: Scarecrow Press, 2005.

Series II: Sheet Music, 1932-1982. This series contains sheet music of politically-themed songs written by Gorney, as well as lyric sheets, and correspondence. Related lyric sheets, correspondence, and printed materials are filed with the sheet music.
